<font color="#FF0000">TO &quot;A VET&quot; AND OTHERS.......</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 12 21:53:00 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
&quot;A Vet&quot;<br><br>
Frankly, your argument about awards being given or not, to those of clandestine ops does nothing for me and I truely don't want to get into it. I, however, am curious about when and where you tromped the bush as it seems we have that in common. I was in I Corps from Nov. 67, and we moved down to the Parrots Beak region in, roughly, Oct. 68 until I left in Feb of '70, just before the incursion into Cambodia. E-mail me if you will, so that we may compare notes.<br><br>
To all the above<br><br>
Some vets hate the awards they got. Some think they represent who they are. Some think not a twit about their medals gathering dust in their closet. Some folks get offended when you mention what you were awarded. Some get bored. And some get excited.<br><br>
I got a my share of awards. I understand that it was easier for medics to get them because they tend to be in the forefront during the shit, thus, more noticable, to those recommending. I have two PH's, because I was wounded twice. They mean little to me, when standing along side my kid. How about we try to put life today in some perspective and the awards we recieved and get back to the topic of this thread.
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


